<h2>7.4 WIA Braille Integration</h2>

<h3>7.4.1 Overview</h3>

<p>WIA Braille is the standard for converting text to braille notation. It supports multiple braille codes and can output to refreshable braille displays.</p>

<h3>7.4.2 Integration API</h3>

<pre>
import { WiaAAC } from 'wia-aac';
import { WiaBraille, BrailleDisplay } from 'wia-braille';

// Initialize
const aac = new WiaAAC();
const braille = new WiaBraille({
    code: 'UEB',  // Unified English Braille
    grade: 2      // Grade 1 (letter-by-letter) or Grade 2 (contracted)
});

// Connect to braille display
const display = await BrailleDisplay.connect();

// Connect AAC to Braille
aac.on('text', async (text) =&gt; {
    // Convert to braille
    const brailleText = braille.convert(text);

    // Send to display
    await display.write(brailleText);
});

// Get braille unicode
aac.on('text', (text) =&gt; {
    const brailleUnicode = braille.toUnicode(text);
    console.log(brailleUnicode);
    // Output: "⠓⠑⠇⠇⠕" for "hello"
});
</pre>

<h3>7.4.3 Braille Code Support</h3>

<pre>
Supported Braille Codes:

Grade 1 (Uncontracted):
  - Letter-by-letter transcription
  - Used for beginners and technical text

Grade 2 (Contracted):
  - Uses contractions for common words
  - Standard for most braille readers

Code Standards:
  - UEB (Unified English Braille) - International
  - EBAE (English Braille American Edition) - US
  - Korean Braille - Korea
  - Japanese Braille - Japan
  - And 30+ national codes

Conversion Example:
Input: "Hello World"

Grade 1: ⠓⠑⠇⠇⠕ ⠺⠕⠗⠇⠙
Grade 2: ⠓⠑⠇⠇⠕ ⠺⠕⠗⠇⠙ (same for these words)

Input: "the quick brown fox"

Grade 1: ⠞⠓⠑ ⠟⠥⠊⠉⠅ ⠃⠗⠕⠺⠝ ⠋⠕⠭
Grade 2: ⠮ ⠟⠅ ⠃⠗⠪⠝ ⠋⠕⠭ (contractions used)
</pre>

